\begin_layout Chapter
Decay behaviour of the quasi-particle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter we will investigate the decay behaviour shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Notch-depth-decay"

\end_inset

.
 We will show that for large 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, a 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{t}$
\end_inset

 decay is expected.
 We need to evaluate the expression:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(x,t)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{p,p=-N}^{N}\langle P|\hat{\rho}(0)|P'\rangle e^{i(P-P')x-i(E_{p}-E_{p'})t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we will approximate this double sum as a double integral.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{N}\sum_{p,p=-N}^{N}\langle P|\hat{\rho}(0)|P'\rangle e^{i(P-P')x-i(E_{p}-E_{p'})t}=\frac{1}{N}\int_{\mathbb{R}^{2}}dpdp'A_{p}A_{p'}e^{-iE_{p}t}e^{iE_{p}t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This integral can be approximated with a stationary phase approximation,
 which we will briefly review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stationary phase approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can approximate oscillatory integrals of the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int dpg(p)e^{itf(p)},\qquad t\gg1\label{eq:oscillatory_integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will take advantage of the fact that in regions where 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial f}{\partial p}\neq0$
\end_inset

, the oscillating function 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{itf(p)}$
\end_inset

 kills the integral by destructive interference.
 So only the tiny regions around certain dominant frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 at which 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial f}{\partial p}=0$
\end_inset

 contribute to the value of the integral.
 In these regions, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(p)$
\end_inset

 is essentially constant and we Taylor-expand 
\begin_inset Formula $f(p)$
\end_inset

 to second order:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(p)=f(\omega)+\frac{f''(\omega)}{2}(p-\omega)^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, the first order term is zero by definition of the points 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

.
 Now, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq:oscillatory_integral}$
\end_inset

 can be approximated as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}g(\omega_{i})e^{itf(\omega_{i})}\int_{\mathbb{R}}dpe^{it\frac{f''(\omega_{i})}{2}(p-\omega_{i})^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is large, even a small difference 
\begin_inset Formula $p-\omega_{i}$
\end_inset

 leads to a highly oscillating integrand, resulting in no contribution to
 the total value of the integral.
 This allows us to freely expand the limits of the resulting integrals to
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

.
 They are easily evaluated:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{\mathbb{R}}dpe^{it\frac{f''(\omega_{i})}{2}(p-\omega_{i})^{2}}=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this chapter I will use a stationary phase approximation to show that
 the notch depth decays as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{t}$
\end_inset

 for large 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, as the simulation shows.
 We start with:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int_{\mathbb{R}}dpA_{p}e^{iE(p)t}\label{eq:1d_momentum_integral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is an oscillatory integral with phase term 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi=E(p)t$
\end_inset

.
 We take 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{p}$
\end_inset

 to be constant.
 The values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 varies rapidly do not contribute to the integral.
 We focus on the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 for which the phase term is stationary, that is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\phi}{dp}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\phi}{dp}=\frac{dE(p)}{dp}t=0\implies\frac{dE(p)}{dp}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 that satisfy this equation 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{L}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{R}$
\end_inset

, since it turns out there are two such 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Continue for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{L}=p$
\end_inset

, argument for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{R}$
\end_inset

 analogous.
 Now expand 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $p=p_{L}$
\end_inset

 to second order:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi\approx E(p_{L})t+\frac{1}{2}\frac{d^{2}E}{dp^{2}}(p_{L})t(p_{L}-p)^{2}\equiv E(p_{L})t+\frac{1}{2}\alpha t(p_{L}-p)^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now have the integral:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{\mathbb{R}}dpA_{p}e^{it[E(p_{L})+\frac{1}{2}\alpha(p-p_{L})^{2}]}=\#\int_{\mathbb{R}}dpe^{\frac{it\alpha}{2}p{}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can still integrate over the whole real line for large 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, since then even a small difference 
\begin_inset Formula $(p-p_{L})$
\end_inset

 leads to rapid oscillations of the integrand.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\#$
\end_inset

 denotes different real numbers that are not important in our reasoning.
 In the second step, we shifted the integral from 
\begin_inset Formula $p-p_{L}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
 Now a rescaling 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{p}=p\sqrt{\alpha t}$
\end_inset

 yields:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\#}{\sqrt{t}}\int_{\mathbb{R}}d\bar{p}e^{\frac{i}{2}\bar{p}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since this is a standard variable that does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, we can conclude that our original expression, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ref{eq:1d_momentum_integral}$
\end_inset

, has a 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{-\frac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

 dependence.
 
\end_layout

